It’s a wrap! So grateful for the invitation to enjoy the @whitehouse holiday open house today and represent #OutdoorAfro. I was most struck with the incredible art, and deep pride in our nation’s history celebrating the holidays across various administrations. A treasured memory! 

Thank you Oakland’s @shoptaylorjay for the perfect dress for the occasion!
It’s so thrilling to find a bookstore across the country from my home that sells #natureswagger! And I was able to sign the last copy they had in stock! Thanks for your support @busboysandpoets!

Standing room only! A deeply gratifying and warm time spent this  evening at my local @alibibookshop right here in the @cityofvallejo with the on site support of @chroniclebooks! After  my reading, we had a lovely discussion followed by the chance to sign books and personally connect with many great people. Thank you to my organizers and those who came out to support me and #NatureSwagger !

Such a sad day. My beloved puppy Lulu crossed the rainbow bridge peacefully today after we learned this week that cancer and pain had taken over her body.

She was such a good dog who loved and protected us fiercely for almost a decade. I’m grateful for my bond with her as her pack leader, and the many adventures she got to be a part of in the outdoors. 

She was rescued from an East Oakland junkyard, where her and mate “Trouble” were abandoned after being used for breeding. 

Thankfully the dogs got the attention of an angel neighbor and pitbull rescue team who helped make a connection between Lulu and our home and eventually to our hearts.

I thank all my friends and community who loved on Lulu with us for all these years, and who have provided compassionate advice and comfort in so many ways this week after I got the news.

She took her last breath in front of a wood fire, after a cheeseburger meal, and surrounded by love. Such an honorable and privileged way to say goodbye, and I’ll always be grateful for this. 

Afterwards the kids and I went on a short hike on one of her favorite walks to share how thankful we are to have had this kind of unconditional love and one another.

Such a good girl…see you on the other side 🌈💔

This week was tough, but made so much easier with your caring words, texts, and flowers in remembrance of Lulu. It really made a difference. 

I also decided to holiday foster a sweet rescued pup @adopt_oas_tesla from @oaklandanimalservices and her gentle soul has filled my heart and brought more clarity that there are so many good dogs out there in need of a loving home. She’ll be a great addition to a lucky family. 

Lulu also came home yesterday, and she is back again near her favorite place to always be remembered.

Thank you everyone for your generosity and compassion. Means more than you know. And @lapofloveveterinaryhospice are MVPs for their thorough, compassionate care. 

Happy Holidays,

🌈🐾❤️

EXCITING NEWS: I am hosting the 2023 @goldmanprize San Francisco ceremony! 🌎🏆 

Awarded each year to grassroots environmental activists around the world since 1990, the prestigious #GoldmanPrize honors and supports outstanding leaders fighting to protect our planet.

As someone who has dedicated my career to expanding access to nature and increasing inclusivity outdoors through @outdoorafro, this is a great honor. Goldman Prize winners are truly motivational and inspiring. 

Examples of past Prize winners include environmental justice leader Sharon Lavigne of @risestjames, who successfully stopped the construction of a plastics manufacturing plant alongside the Mississippi River in St. James Parish, Louisiana. There’s also @NalleliCobo, a young activist whose organizing helped usher in a ban on urban oil drilling in Los Angeles.

I hope you’ll join me in meeting the 2023 Prize winners, and learning their stories of bravery and grit in defense of the environment.

📅 Monday, April 24, at 5:30 pm PDT / 8:30 pm EDT
📺 Watch the livestream on the Goldman Environmental Prize @YouTube channel

See you then!

#GoldmanPrize2023 #GoldmanPrize #environment #OutdoorAfro #CEO #NatureSwagger #OutdoorRetailer #outdoors #nature #equipment #conservation

Joy is visiting Anacostia National Park to dive deep into nature and community! So thankful!

@ruemapp transformed her kitchen table blog into a national nature business and movement. Today, she is founder and CEO of @outdoorafro. For more than a decade, the not-for-profit organization has continued to celebrate and inspire Black connections and leadership in nature across the United States. Mapp also is an awarded and inspirational leader, speaker, public lands champion and published author. Her first national book is Nature Swagger: Stories and Visions of Black Joy in the Outdoors(Chronicle Books, 2022). Mapp became a National Geographic 2019 Fellow, Heinz Awards Honoree, and National Wildlife Federation Communication Award recipient as well. 

We are lucky enough to be cohosting a webinar with Rue next Wednesday 26th April. It will be the third conversation in our Empowering Women in Today’s World series, co-presented by the Mesa Refuge, @point_reyes, and  @tnscommonweal . You can find recordings of the first two events—with attorney and immigrant justice movement strategist Marielena Hincapié and author, mother, and reparative justice attorney Lara Bazelon—on the New School’s YouTube playlist, Soundcloud playlist, Apple Podcasts, and Spotify. Watch and/or listen in Spanish or English.

Now as a mother of an active duty US Marine, Memorial Day hits different. 

I remember how my dad used to drag us to the Lower Lake, California Memorial Day parade after a weekend of family fun and frolic, as a sobering reminder of what our weekend was really about. I hear his lectures clearly still in my head (as some of us kids complained about going and how it was “no fun”)

Today, I am ever more thankful for the impress his admonitions and education had on me…

So I am grateful for this day of recognition for all our military who gave the ultimate sacrifice, and my own growing connection to this day as a family. 🇺🇸 #SemperFidelis

Good morning Norway! 🇳🇴

Today, my group and I arrived at the Svalbard archipelago and made our way up to Spitsbergen, the largest of the three main islands. Magnificent brown and green mountains rise and ripple up from the High Arctic tundra while rivers of snow-melt trickle through the valley plains, glistening under the summer sun.

We are just taking in Svalbard. We’re at a latitude more than 78°N and less than 820 miles from the North Pole. The air is fresh and pure, and the overall temperature in summer is mild, thanks to a warm northern branch of the Gulf Stream.

We disembarked the ship (farewell amazing crew!) at Longyearbyen, nestled on the banks of a sweeping fjord. It is the biggest settlement in Svalbard and pegged as the world’s northernmost settlement with a population over 1,000.

Home to some 2,000 inhabitants from across the world, it originally sprang up as a coal mining colony in 1906. Today, it is a hub for adventure travelers and scientists and engineers attached to local research projects, like the famous Global Seed Vault.

After checking in to our hotel, it’s then on to Camp Barentz, located at the foot of Breinosa mountain, for a true Svalbard wilderness evening. There, we will enjoy dinner in a cozy wooden cabin and maybe even try some bidos (a traditional, homemade Sámi stew of slow-cooked reindeer meat and vegetables).
Savor our dessert around the campfire, perhaps under the Midnight Sun. End the day admiring the mountains as we head back to our lodge.

(More photo details about our day in my upcoming stories!)

I am exceptionally grateful to return from an incredible community and wilderness experience this last week!

(And yes, this meant no internet or flush toilets!)

My @americanleadership Silicon Valley class XLIII embarked on its annual flagship group experience to cement our bonds and contemplate leadership in an exquisite multi-day, climb and summit of the Sierra Buttes!

Climbing to heights that reached the 8000+ ft summit, we shared gifts and strengths along the way with one another that will be remembered and deployed for a lifetime.

For me personally, I always value having at least one wilderness experience each year, but I had not summited in the Sierra mountain region for nearly 30 years as an Outward Bound student, around the tender age of 20, when I learned how I could “trust my feet “– a lesson that would last and serve me for a lifetime. 

So last week, it was incredible to belay others and climb to trust my feet all over again in a completely transformed body that has since birthed three children and launched a purpose filled career. 

I am as proud as I am grateful for continued strength that embodies that applied perseverance throughout the years.

I also have come to appreciate that now being north of 50 years, how important it is to model and invite more people to participate in active aging, so I am ever more inspired to continue living by and sharing this message with others in my community!

I give so much thanks to the ALF staff, the wonderful family hosts at Gold Lake, our wilderness staff, and all the incredible participants in my class who gave themselves over completely and so generously to this life-changing experience.

I was so happy to hunt as a guest just before Thanksgiving Day with #BlackHeritageHunt alums Dan Castilow, then back again for my own lottery win with Angelo Paez at Grizzly Ranch in Suisun, CA. 

The weather was mild with stunning sunrises, and the Saturday hunt brought more wind that kept the ducks flying. 

Each of my blind partners experienced huge wins and accomplished important milestones - Dan’s enthusiastic pup Eugene experienced his first waterfowl hunt and was a great companion all around, while helping him take home two birds.

On Saturday Angelo brought down his most ducks at one time, (also captained the boat for us as a first!) I watched with pride as he gave it his all working the ducks with calls and shooting so well!

The joy of supporting and encouraging newer hunters never gets old, and I’m honored to share the journey as I continually learn myself. 

Admittedly, my own performance was perplexing on both days, to say the least. In spite of many good shooting opportunities each day, I could not shoot the side of a barn! 

Perhaps it was because I missed last season entirely due to work demands - and as a re-entry hunter that might have represented a significant setback for this year. Or maybe I need a new choke? Or more time at the range? Who knows, maybe it’s a bit of all the above …but overall I remain very motivated to work hard and recover whatever I lost for this season with at least three more planned hunts on the calendar before it ends. 

And I am reminded about the humble pie hunting stays ready to serve us and the satisfaction that comes from the sum of it all. My hunting crew was thoughtfully safe. My decoy spread was very attractive to the ducks, and our blind food from home was fire! It’s the *entire* experience is why I keep coming back. 

I am filled with so much joy and gratitude for the lessons, wins big and small, and the chance to incrementally better prepare for whatever possibilities come my way.

@dcastilow 
@angelo_paez17 
@calwaterfowl

I always say I’m not a baker.

Instead, I typically outsource cakes, pies, and cobblers from friends or favorite local soul food restos, but my girl Talithia @ogtalithia challenged me this week to overcome my doubts and give it a try, with her mom’s generously shared recipe for 7-Up cake with me — that happens to be among my hubby’s favorite treats! 

As you can see, the lead up was imperfect, but with a little finishing finesse, the final taste and review from hubby was so good, we wont’t need to go to outside the home to get a 7-Up cake ever again! 

H/T to my girl KK @kgkinspired for gifting me perfect serving dish way back when for such a special moment!
